\nmillion from a year before.\u2014\nFederal Reserve Board.\nRailroad Freight Loadings last\nweek totaled 544,173 cars. This\ntotal for the week ended March\n8. was 9,472 cars on 1.7 per;\ncent below the preceeding\nweek. 128,190 cars or 19.1 per\ncent below the same week in\n1957 and 153.428 cars or 22 per\ncent under the same week in\n1956. \u2014Association of American\nRailroads.\nAmerican exports in Janu\nary totaled $1,510,900,000, a\ndrop of 8 per cent from De\ncember and about 10 per cent\nbelow January a year ago.\nThe total included about SIOB\nmillion of military shipments.\n\u2014Commerce Department.\nWestern Maryland Railway\nreports net income of $125,000\nfor February compared with\n$711,000 for the same month\nof 1957. For the fidt two\nmonths of 1958, net income\nwas $563,000 or 71 cents a\nshare, as compared with $4,-\n394,000 or $1.98 a share for the\nlike period last year.\nKennecott Copper reports\n1957 net income came to $79,-\n251.867, equal to $7.32 a share\nof common stock, compared\nwith net of $143,154,210 or\n$12.23 a share in the record\nyear 1956. Sales were $480.-\n199,520 against $576,067,252\nthe previous year.\nInternational Paper earn\nings declined 10 per cent in\n1957, while sales dipped 3 per\n'cent. Net profit was $78,387,891.\nequal to 86.17 per common\nshare compared with the 1956\nearnings of 886.628.013 or $6.85\na share. Sales of $940,427,571\ncompared with the record\n$969,618,438 in 1956.\nSeaboard Air Line Railroad\nreports net income in 1957 to\ntaled 818.509.148. equal to 83.85\na common share, compared\nwith 820.145.391 or $4.20 a\nshare in 1956.\nOther earnings:\nPar Six Manlha Ended Jan. 31\n195* 1957\nCollins Radio. $569,590 $2,346.0.16\nPer share 0 37 1.48\nPar the Yaar Ended Dea. .$1\nAmer Maracaibo 3.083.83.1 2.585.004\nPar share 0.84 0.73\nRexall Drux 4.H13.835 4.473.588\nPer share 1.46 135\nHerdn Npt Ch 2.582.000 2..554.000\nPer share l .oS 1.07!\nA B Du Mont Lab\nNet loss 535.000 3.887.000 1\nDennison Mfx 2.103 000 2.817.000\nPer share 3 25 4 50\nCHICAGO GRAIN\nCHICAOO. Mar. 14 IP \u2014Most grain\nfutures prices turned decidedly weak\ntoday on the Board of Trade after a\nsteady opening\nEven the old crop wheat contracts,\nwhich have been consistent! strong\nduring the Jaat govern) days of re\nports of rapidly dlmlxhlng cash supply,\ncame under fairly liberal offerings and\nthose prices sagged along with nearly\nall the others\nNew crop wheat and rye. the bread\ngrains, were the heaviest losers In the\nearly dealings Traders said commis\nsion houses were among the sellers\nend that the liquidation tn wheat was\nprimarily the result of the Senate I\naction yesterday on the bills to extend\nall l\u00bb5(l Government farm price sup\nports to the 1058 crops\nNear the end of the flrst hour wheat\nwas 1 to cents a bushel lower.\nMarch'l.M*: corn 3 to H lower.\nMarch 1,51 oats lower. March\nry* to Va lower. March\nsoybeans to 4, lower. March 2.2?+;\nand lard 5 to 10 cents a houndred\npounds higher. March 12.5*.\nNEW YORK COTTON\nnew YORK Mar 14 IP\u2014Cotton\nfutures weakened during the late\nmorning as liquidation Increasad mod\nerately. Only scale-down support was\nIn evidence with prices giving (round 1\nreadily on small volume m\nThe New York Cotton Exchange\nService estimated domestic cotton con-II\nsumption tor February '.\u2019-March I at\ns.oon jialcs. against 700.1MM1 tn the\nprecedlnt live-week period and 888.-!'\nnno for February l-March 2 a veer,\nago. Indicated consumption this gee\nson for the ill) weeks. August 4-March,,\n1. Is 4.828.(810 bales against 5.268.-\n000 In the .11 weeks from July 20 to\nMarch 2. 1057.\nNoon prices were AO cents to SI a\nbale lower than the previous close.\nMav 35 65. July 85 81 and Oct. 3(1.09.1\nNYCea M 90+\nN Y Tala 4+a *1 109*\nNat Pac ISO 00*\nNorthrop 4a 75 09+\nOtia Math s** \u00ab3 10**\nOrWaahRRNM M 100\nPae G ft E 244a Tl 100+\nPh\u00dfMse Pal 4+a 17 100+\nPubSvEftG \u00ab%eT7 109*\nRCA 3+alb 99*\nRtadg3*a96 67*\nRapa Tab la 72 04*\nItahr Aire s+a 77 100*\nRoyal Mc\u00dfae (*4a 77 100*\nSi L S F Sa 3006 99*\nScott Paper M 71 90*\nSinclair 4* M 109+\nSmith Oar (a 1\u00bb 100*\nSo Cal Ed 3+a Tb 114\nSoaJ>aes+aS3 109\nSa Pac 0( 4+a 77 94*\nStd O lad 3+a 12 100\nStd O NJ 2+a 71 00*\nSsperiorOU 3*lll 90\nTax Carp 3445 09\nrev ft NO 34+ tt 73\nThoaa Prel+a U 100*\nIJaGaaCp44wT! 102\nVaaadhmi 4+a 74 92\nFORRMN 1:15\nAaalraHa 3*B tt 90*\nBaU*M 00*\nChile la tt 30*\nOrlwd ntettal 99*\nUaSeaAfrteaSVxatt 97*\nMcDoaatd Aire lb 17\nMeacace .15* 9\nMolybden .44 17*\nNaw Eng Tft T S 139\nNoma Light! *1 9*\nNorbute 4*\nNerd Ketay 3\nNo Can Oil! 2*VU!\nNertheron Urea wta 2*\nOgden Cp 11\nO'Kiep lie 91\nPac Patrol Ltd 17*\nP anconal Pat *t 9*\nRapid Am 19\nRoosevelt Race \u2019it 6*\nSt Lawrence Cp 1 14+\nScurry Rain 2*H\u00bb\nScab ft W Ail *1 6+\nSeemaa Brea 12+\nSignal Oil A DO 37*\nSinge: Mfg 2.2 P 37+\nStd Dredge 10c 0*\nSym Wayne war 2*\nTeehoico 3*\nTbew Shov el 20a 24+\nTri Cont wts 16*\nUM Aire Pd Via 6*4\n.Ltd Aaboatai 9*\u00ab\nU S Foil P ,40a 2d*\nUaiv Marion l.Mb 14*\nWebb ft Knapp 1\nWmi Me Wmi Ha 12*\nRetail Buying\nRises Slightly\nOver Nation\nNEW YORK. Mar. 14 (*F).\u2014\nRetail trade Improved this\nweek under the Impetus of\nearly Easter buying, sparked by\nwarmei weather and new style\ninterest. Dun Bradstreet Inc.\nreported today.\nConsumer buying was slightly\nhigher than a year zgo. Re\nflecting abandonment of fair\ntrade policies by some man\nufacturers, sales of small elec\ntrical appliances maintained\ntheir high level of the pre\nvious week, considerable higher\nthan a year ago.\nTotal retail sales in the week\nended Wednesday ranged from\n1 to 5 per cent higher than the\ncorresponding week in 1957, ac\ncording to spot estimates in\nthe survey.\nRegional estimates varied\nfrom their comparable year-ago\nlevels by the following per\ncentages:\nMiddle Atlantic, plus 7 to\nplus II;\nSouth Atlantic, plus 3 to\nplus 7;\nNew England and Mountain,\nplus 1 to plus 5:\nPacific, 0 to plus 4;\nEast North Central, minus 1\nto plus 2;\nWest North Central, minus 2\nto plus 2;\nEast South Central and West\nSouth Central, minus 1 to plus\n5.\nApparel reorders were higher,\nwith an apreciable rise for\nwomen's spring coats and suits.\nTRADE\nWINDS\nBy LOU SCHNEIDER\nMen who back their opinions\nwith millions of dollars show\nno apprehension about the bus\niness outlook for the second\nhalf of the year.\nYes, they expect unpleasant\nreading in corporate first\nquarter financial reports, cau\ntious statements by corporate\nmanagements at the spring\nflood of annual stockholder\nmeetings, and even a continued\nflow of dividend reductions.\nBut from intimate banking\nfriends they hear the odds are\nagainst a spiraling downtrend\nto depression levels. They hear\nthere will be a leveling out of\nthe recession over the next four\nto six months. In other words,\nthere are signs of stabilization.\nTo put it another way, the\nmajor part of the recession has\nbeen passed. A flat bottom will\nbe held for several months fol\nlowed by a recovery. The\nrecovery will be slow but good,\nnot a fast thriller.\n\nCanada also is in an economic\ndecline Opinion Is that no real\nupturn is likely as long as there\nis a lack of export demand for\nlumber, wood products and\nmetals. Right now there is a\nworld oversupply because of a\nworld-wide easing In business\nactivity.\nLondon reports a world-wide\nrush to buy gold. More than\nS2OO million of the monetary\nmetal has been taken for pri\nvate hoarding in the last few\nmonths. West Germans ac\ncount for about half\u2014having\nsad knowledge of currency de\npreciation. And American In\nvestors are following the trend.\nNot being able to own the metal\nlegally, they are buying se\ncurities of gold mining com\npanies. It's partly due to re\ncession psychological fright,\nbeing fully aware that the\nUnited States will not increase\nits $35-per-ounce fixed price, i\nBut In foreign lands the boom\nrides high, in gold bars and\ncoins. Most gold coins were\nminted before the gold stand\nard was generally abandoned i\nin the early 19305. A United\nStates eagle ($10), with about\nsls gold value. Is priced ati\ni 521.50 in West Germany. The!\ndouble eagle \u00bbS2O gold coin) is\npriced at $42.\nNc*i natural)\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C. *9.\nFRIDAY. MARCH l\u00ab. 1888\nBenefits of Easy Money\nBegin to Aid Consumer\nBy SAM DAWSON\nAitoclated Preti Financial Writer\nNEW YORK. Mar. 14 (A 5\nThe consumer who borrows to\nbuy\u2014either on the instalment\nplan or in a lump sum from the\nbank\u2014may see little change so\nfar under the new easier money\npolicy. But as those who fi\nnance his purchases And a\nlarger supply of credit to tap\nat lower rates, the benefits are\nbeginning to trickle down to\nthe on-the-cuff man.\nEasy money as counter-agent\nto recession may have been\naimed primarily at making it\neasier for the businessman and\nthe home builder to borrow.\nBut the huge role of consumer\nin the economy and the sizable\npart that credit plays in to- j\nday\u2019s family budgets throws a\nspotlight on consumer loans.\nTrend Watched\nTheir trend will be watched\nclosely in the next two months\n|by those charting the business\ncycle.\nTight money for months ap\npeared to have little effect on\nthe steady upward climb of\ntotal consumer debt. Only con\ntraction of the repayment\nperiod did much to brake it.\n\u201cThe average purchaser pays\nlittle attention to the amount\nof the interest charge involved\nin his instalment loan.\u201d says\nthe head of one of the largest\nfinance companies. \u201cWhaf he\nlooks at is the size of the\nmonthly payment in relation to\nhis paycheck.\u201d\nBut tight money caught up\nwith the finance companies.\nThey have to borrow funds\nneeded to carry your time pur\nchases. As the supply of these\navailable funds shrank and the\ninterest costs climbed steadily,\nfinance companies raised the\ncharges for the funds they in\neffect lend to the car dealer or\nthe appliance retailer to pay\nthe manufacturer while carry\ning on-the-cuff customers.\nAbout this time competition\nsot so tough between dealers\nand retailers that they absorbed\nsome of this rise and for awhile\nlet it squeeze profits. Last fall\nthey began to pass on new\ncosts along with higher prices\non their goods\nInstalment Debt Cut\nIn January consumers cut\ntheir outstanding instalment\ndebt by $368 million. Part of\nthis was seasonal, part the\nshrinking of many incomes, bus\npart could have been reaction\nMETAL PRICES\nNEW YORK. Mar 14 14V\u2014Spot\nmetal prices today Copper J3-C5\nj cents a pound. Connecticut valley\n\u25a0Lead 13 cents a pound. New York.\nZinc 10 cents i pound. East Bt. Louis.\nTin 05 rents a nound. New York\ni Foreign stiver cents per troy\nounce. New York Pittsburgh scrap\nsteel No 1 heavy 3? 00-3* 00.\nSTATEMENT OF THE CONDITION\nOF THE\nMIDWESTERW UNITED LIFE\nINSURANCE COMPANY\n-2ft West Berry Street, of Fort Wayne.\nIndiana, on the 31st dav of December.\nIPST.\nASSETS\nBonds and stocks fd.534.054 69\nMortgage loans on real\nestate 3.8fif1.4ft.Y04\nReal estate 41C.91906\nPolicy loans and premi\nums notes 562.315,9\u201d\nCash and bank deposits 446.156 15\nPremiums deferred and\nuncollected 788.484 71\nInterest and other in\nvestment income due\nand accrued 53.975 08\nOther assets 4 .\\HK8.4\u00ab\nTotal assets $1.1j057.87ft.il\nLIABILITIES\nAggregate reserve for\npolicies and contracts $8.179 614 01\nPolicy and contract\nclaims 11.955.20\nlability for policyhold\ners' dividends 1.777.665 24\nOther poliev and con\ntract liabilities 227.046,63\nOther liabilities 350.965 60\nTotal liabilities $10,547,246.68'\nCapital paid up 50n.000.n0\nSurnlus 2.010,642.43\nTotal $13.057,889.11\nSUMMARY OF OPERATIONS\nPremiums and annuit?\nconsiderations $4,992,770.77\nConsiderations for sup\nplementary contracts 139.952.18\nNet Investment Income\nand capital gains 4R4.588.97\nother Income 444.771.34\nTotal \"$6.062.083.26\nDeath benefits and 